First off, this one falls outside my circle of competence. I’ve spent over six decades investing in simple, consumer‐oriented businesses I can wrap my arms around—Coca-Cola, See’s Candies, Apple’s ecosystem—and I confess I don’t fully grasp the nitty-gritty of Google’s advertising algorithms, cloud offerings and AI initiatives. Having insufficient fundamental and moat data only reinforces that view.

As for a competitive moat, Google clearly has scale and network effects in search and digital ads. But I can’t measure its durability or how quickly new AI rivals or regulation might chip away at that advantage. The management team is undoubtedly bright, yet Alphabet’s history of pouring capital into moonshots—some of which never pay off—makes me uneasy about forecasting sensible capital allocation.

With no financials provided, I can’t judge balance sheet strength, earnings consistency or intrinsic value. No margin of safety calculations here means I’d be flying blind on price versus worth. Long term, the business might prosper; it might also face fierce competition from nimble players or political headwinds.

Compared to opportunities I understand—like Coca-Cola’s pricing power or Apple’s sticky ecosystem—Google doesn’t light me up. When in doubt, the answer is usually “no.” So I’d pass and stick to the arenas I know best.
